       This  manual  page  documents the GNU version of uuppddaatteeddbb,
       which updates file name databases used by GNU llooccaattee.  The
       file  name  databases  contain lists of files that were in
       particular directory trees when the  databases  were  last
       updated.   The file name of the default database is deter-
       mined  when  llooccaattee  and  uuppddaatteeddbb  are   configured   and
       installed.   The  frequency  with  which the databases are
       updated and the directories for which they contain entries
       depend  on how often uuppddaatteeddbb is run, and with which argu-
       ments.

       In networked environments, it often makes sense to build a
       database  at  the  root of each filesystem, containing the
       entries for that filesystem.  uuppddaatteeddbb  is  then  run  for
       each filesystem on the fileserver where that filesystem is
       on a local disk, to prevent thrashing the network.   Users
       can  select which databases llooccaattee searches using an envi-
       ronment variable or command line option;  see  llooccaattee(1L).
       Databases can not be concatenated together.

       The  file  name  database format changed starting with GNU
       ffiinndd and llooccaattee version 4.0 to allow machines with diffent
       byte orderings to share the databases.  The new GNU llooccaattee
       can read both the old and new database formats.   However,
       old  versions of llooccaattee and ffiinndd produce incorrect results
       if given a new-format database.

